what is Amazon Corretto’s GPG key and why? what is rpm and yum?

Amazon Corretto’s GPG key

It is a digital public key used to verify that the package really came from Amazon Corretto and was not changed by someone in between.

Why it is needed

When your server downloads Java packages, it should check:

Is this package really from Amazon?

Was it modified or corrupted?

That check is done using GPG signature verification.

Real-world example

Think like this:

Amazon sends a parcel

parcel has official seal/signature

your system already knows Amazon’s sample signature

it compares both

if matching, it trusts the parcel

So:

GPG key = trusted sample signature

package signature = seal on delivered parcel

If both match, system says:

okay, safe to install

Why specifically Amazon Corretto’s GPG key?

Because you are installing Amazon Corretto Java from Amazon’s repository.

So your Linux machine must know:

“When I download Corretto packages, this is the official public key I should use to verify them.”

Without that key, your server cannot properly validate the package source.

What is rpm?

rpm stands for:

RPM Package Manager

It is a package management tool used in Linux distributions like:

RHEL

CentOS

Oracle Linux

Amazon Linux

Rocky Linux

What it does

It helps to:

install packages

remove packages

query installed packages

verify packages

import GPG keys

In simple words

rpm works directly with .rpm package files.

Real-world example

Think of rpm like a package handling clerk.

It can:

open a software box

install it

check its details

verify its signature

Example:

rpm -qa

This shows installed RPM packages.

Example:

rpm --import somekey

This imports a trusted signature key.

So in your command:

rpm --import https://yum.corretto.aws/corretto.key

rpm is being used only to store the trusted key in the system.

What is yum?

yum stands for:

Yellowdog Updater Modified

It is a higher-level package manager that works on top of RPM-based systems.

What it does

It helps to:

install software

remove software

update software

resolve dependencies automatically

download packages from repositories

In simple words

yum is smarter than plain rpm.

Because yum does not just install one package.
It also checks:

where to download from

what dependencies are needed

what extra packages should be installed

Real-world example

Think like this:

rpm:

You manually bring one box home and install it yourself.

yum:

You go to a supermarket with a shopping system.
You ask for one item, and it automatically adds related required items too.

For example, if Java package needs some dependency, yum can fetch that too.

Difference between rpm and yum
rpm

low-level package tool

works directly with .rpm packages

does not handle dependencies well by itself

used for package-level operations

yum

high-level package manager

uses repositories

downloads packages automatically

handles dependencies

easier for installation and updates

Easy real-world analogy

Think of software installation like buying and setting up office equipment.

rpm

A worker who can unpack and register a single item.

yum

A manager who:

knows which store to buy from

gets all required items

ensures everything needed is brought together

So usually:

rpm = package-level worker

yum = full purchasing system

In your command flow
1. rpm --import ...

Store Amazon’s trusted signature

2. curl ... corretto.repo

Save Amazon Corretto repo address

3. yum install ...

Download and install Java from that repo

Super simple final memory

GPG key = trusted digital signature sample

rpm = low-level package tool

yum = high-level package installer using repositories

One-line memory:

rpm handles packages, yum fetches and installs packages smartly, GPG key makes sure package is genuine.




1) Repository
What is repository?

A repository is a storage location/server from where Linux downloads software packages.

Simple meaning

It is like an online software shop.

Your server goes there and says:

I need Java
I need Git
I need Docker

and downloads them.

Real-world example

Like Amazon/Flipkart store for software packages.

Instead of buying physical items, your Linux machine downloads software from there.

In your example

https://yum.corretto.aws/corretto.repo

This is telling your system:

Amazon Corretto repository is available here

So from this repo, system can install Corretto Java.

2) Package
What is package?

A package is the actual software file/application bundle that gets installed.

Simple meaning

It is the software box.

For example:

Java package

Git package

Nginx package

Real-world example

Repository is the shop
Package is the product box inside the shop

So:

Repo = store

Package = item/product in store

Example
yum install -y java-17-amazon-corretto-devel

Here:

java-17-amazon-corretto-devel

is the package name.

That package contains:

java binary

javac compiler

libraries

files needed for Java 17 JDK

3) Dependency
What is dependency?

A dependency is another package/software required for the main package to work properly.

Simple meaning

Main software cannot work alone.
It needs supporting software.

Real-world example

Suppose you buy a printer.

Printer alone is not enough.
You may also need:

power cable

driver software

ink cartridge

USB cable

These supporting things are like dependencies.

Software example

Suppose you install one application.
That application may need:

a specific library

runtime

helper package

common tools

Those are dependencies.

Why yum is useful?

Because yum automatically checks and installs dependencies.

So if package needs 3 more supporting packages, yum brings all of them.

That is why yum is called smarter than rpm.

4) GPG check
What is GPG check?

A GPG check means verifying the digital signature of the package before installing it.

Simple meaning

System checks:

Is this package really from the original trusted source?
Was it changed or tampered with?

Real-world example

Like checking:

official seal on parcel

bank signature on cheque

company stamp on certificate

If signature is valid, package is trusted.

If not, installation may fail or warn.

Connect all 4 together with one story

Suppose your Linux server wants Java.

Step 1: Repository

Server first needs to know which store to go to
→ That is repository

Step 2: Package

Then it selects the software box/product
→ That is package

Step 3: Dependency

While installing, it may realize it also needs supporting items
→ Those are dependencies

Step 4: GPG check

Before accepting the package, it verifies official seal/signature
→ That is GPG check

Super easy table in words
Repository

Where software is stored

Package

The software item to install

Dependency

Supporting software needed by main package

GPG check

Security check to verify package authenticity

